content:
A code for property management and maintenance using 3D modeling tools could look like this:
```javascript
// Load 3D model of the property
const model = loadModel('property_model.obj');

// Define hotspots for areas of interest (e.g. plumbing, electrical, HVAC)
const hotspots = [
  { name: 'Plumbing', position: [10, 5, 5], radius: 1 },
  { name: 'Electrical', position: [2, 2, 10], radius: 1.5 },
  { name: 'HVAC', position: [-5, 5, -10], radius: 2 },
];

// Add hotspots to the model and attach event listeners
hotspots.forEach((hotspot) => {
  const sphere = createSphere(hotspot.radius);
  sphere.position.set(...hotspot.position);
  model.add(sphere);

  sphere.addEventListener('click', () => {
    showMaintenancePopup(hotspot);
  });
});

function showMaintenancePopup(hotspot) {
  // Use information about the hotspot to show a maintenance popup
  const popup = document.createElement('div');
  popup.innerHTML = `<h3>${hotspot.name} Maintenance</h3><p>There is a leak in the plumbing. Schedule repairs?</p><button>Schedule Repairs</button>`;
  popup.style.position = 'absolute';
  popup.style.top = '50%';
  popup.style.left = '50%';
  popup.style.transform = 'translate(-50%, -50%)';
  document.body.appendChild(popup);
}
```
This code loads a 3D model of a property and adds hotspots to the model for areas of interest, such as plumbing, electrical, and HVAC. When a user clicks on a hotspot, a maintenance popup is displayed with information about the issue and options for scheduling repairs. This can be a useful tool for property managers and maintenance personnel to identify and address issues in a property.
